        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "5dfd02be5f926fcd",
        "text": "offray\nvia [https://matrix.to/#/!bQveTkYXFyxLJQwcLG:matrix.org/$PChzyqu7-8k62TLJ1bN3idGDESYM78otz05XqfRvh88?via=matrix.org&via=dreyeck.freedombox.rocks&via=dagarten.modular.im matrix]\nYeah, I was interpreting \"stack\" loosely as a parsimonious set of software one can be productive with. Lots of developers don't like the P(hp) in LAMP either :)\nAnd I feel pretty productive with Pharo/GT + Fossil + TW. I think that stack names, when \"sticky\", help to spread the ideas embodied on the stack. But when I coined \"pocket infrastructures\" (in an academic context, instead of a development one) I was trying to signal something different about how, when choosing infrastructure, we're choosing by action or omission the people who will use it.\n\nIf the digital infrastructure is something always online, browser/web native, big data, machine training oriented, (that I use instead of machine\"learning\") and all that shiny terms (coming usually from the Global North), we are going to pick the people who has \"proper\" connectivity and machines to run the shiny terminology powered stuff. When the criteria about infrastructure is that it should be able to run in stuff that has the processing/storage power that fits your pocket/backpack, there is an implicit assumption about who will be able to run the infrastructure, hopefully a more diverse and plural one.\n\nInfrastructure is a way to organize inclusion/exclusion.\n\n"
